  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a direct violation of financial regulations. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (from activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, etc.) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This practice is illegal in most jurisdictions and is strictly prohibited under various national and international laws. Financial institutions are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and prevent such activities. Non-compliance with these regulations can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines, legal action, and reputational damage for the institutions involved.",
